    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"883399\">@Matteo Bianchetti</span> you accidentally included two unnecessary lines at the end:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">have</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">l</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Even</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">3</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">norm_num</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">at</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h1</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">contradiction</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"110064\">@Kenny Lau</span> We'd (I worked with him on this) like all of the above. For example the minimal <code>grind</code> tactic proof is great to see. We'd also like a critique of our proof, which works by showing that 2x must be even, while 3 is odd. Could we have done that proof slicker? Of course we want some balance between shortness and doability by us. Such balance is difficult to define precisely.</p>",
